# Documentation Rules

Default: do **not** generate **member-level** XML doc comments (`/// <summary>` on fields,
properties, or methods) unless Tier 1 applies, or the user explicitly asks. Prefer names that
are self-explanatory. Every **public type** still needs the Tier 3 one-line summary (see below).

Explain **why**, not **what**, for member `//` comments and type remarks. Do not restate the next
line of code. (Type-level summaries under Tier 3 below are a narrow, explicitly-scoped exception —
see there.)

## Where docs live (placement)

| Kind of information | Where it goes |
|---|---|
| What the **type** is / its boundary | Type `/// <summary>` (Tier 3 floor) |
| Cross-cutting invariant of the **whole type** | Type `/// <remarks>` |
| Non-obvious contract of a **specific member** | One-line `//` above that member |
| Usage-protocol exceptions on a public API | Optional `/// <exception>` on that member (**no** member `/// <summary>`) |

**Do not** put member-specific why in the type `<remarks>`. If the sentence names a member
(`CooldownQuery`, `IsValid`, `OnHitBuff`), it belongs next to that member as `//`.

Type `<remarks>` stay short and type-scoped, e.g.:
- who constructs / owns the type
- what must not hold this type (e.g. not cached on a factory-created `IAbility` flyweight)
- how the type is meant to be obtained (e.g. self-buff via `ToAbilityTarget`)

```csharp
// Correct — member footgun next to the member
// Read-only surface; mutable cooldown state stays on CooldownManager in AbilitySystem.
public readonly ICooldownQuery CooldownQuery;
```

Rule of thumb: **类型说边界，成员说脚枪；句子里出现成员名，就写在成员上的 `//`。**

## XML cross-references

In XML doc comments, name **same-type** members (fields, properties, methods on the documented type)
with `<c>Name</c>` — not `<see cref="Name"/>`. Reserve `<see cref="…"/>` for **other types** (or
their members) the reader may navigate to. Enum members on the documented enum (e.g. `<c>True</c>`
on `DamageType`) follow the same rule.

## When XML docs are allowed (three tiers)

Judge by **role**, not by a fixed class-name whitelist. Examples below are illustrative.

### Tier 1 — Project-wide contracts

Cross-cutting APIs that define how layers talk to each other (typically Core, but not limited to
the Core folder). Full XML is appropriate: `/// <summary>`, `<typeparam>`, `<exception>`,
`<remarks>` as needed.

Examples: `IEvent`, `IEventBus`, `IState`, `StateMachine`, `IReadOnlyStatCollection`.

Concrete types that only implement a Tier-1 interface: use `/// <inheritdoc/>` on matching public
members instead of duplicating docs.

### Tier 2 — Non-obvious member contracts

When a **member** has a non-obvious precondition, provenance, or call path:

1. Put a one-line `//` above that member (**preferred**), or
2. Only if the same fact applies to several members / the type as a whole, put it in type
   `<remarks>` (see Placement).

Never use `/// <summary>` on fields, properties, or methods for Tier 2. Optional:
`/// <exception>` on a public method/ctor **without** a member summary when the throw encodes
usage protocol and tools benefit from it.

Cross-asmdef consumption is a typical case, not the gate — same-assembly public members (e.g.
`Damageable.ClampCurrentHealthToMax`) qualify when the why is non-obvious. Self-explanatory
public members stay undocumented.

Non-obvious contract includes:
- **Usage protocol** — call order or initialization (e.g. `GetValue` before `SetBaseStat` →
  `InvalidOperationException`).
- **Domain validation on open types** — reject values the type system still allows (e.g. negative
  `float` damage/heal).
- **Value provenance** — who sets a field and when (e.g. crit rolled at the ability layer via
  `IRandomProvider`, not inside the pipeline).
- **Visibility / call path** — public but not the normal entry point (e.g. clamp normally driven
  by `StatChangedEvent`).

**When is a thrown exception part of the public contract?** Document it (member `//`, or
`<exception>` without member summary) when the parameter type allows illegal values **and** real
or architecturally allowed call paths can pass variable/computed values into this API. Omit
documentation for constructor null checks on required dependencies — fail-fast, not usage protocol.

Examples: `StatCollection.AddModifier` / `GetValue`; `Damageable.TakeDamage` / `Heal`;
`DamageContext.IsCrit` (field `//` for provenance); `Damageable.ClampCurrentHealthToMax`.

Usually **omit** documenting every `ArgumentNullException` — prefer exceptions that encode
**usage protocol** (call A before B, or else throw).

### Tier 3 — Everything else

Members: no XML. Self-explanatory public members and internal helpers stay uncommented.

Types: every **public** class/interface/struct/enum still gets at least one `/// <summary>` line,
even when none of its members qualify for Tier 1/2 and would otherwise get zero documentation.
This is a portfolio/reviewer-legibility floor, not a contract-documentation tier — it exists so
opening `StatType.cs` or `StatModifierType.cs` cold gives an immediate sense of the type's role,
without implying its members carry any usage protocol worth documenting. Tier 3 is a **floor**,
not a ceiling: if the type later carries cross-cutting invariants, add `<remarks>` under
Placement rules (type-scoped only).

This one line is the **only** place a slight lean toward "what" is acceptable — naming the type's
role or boundary (e.g. "Additive or Percent contribution applied to a Stat's raw value" for
`StatModifierType`) is fine, since a type has no "next line of code" to restate. It must not:
- restate the type name (`StatType` → ~~"Represents a stat type"~~)
- turn into a members list or usage tutorial
- list member-specific contracts (those go on members as `//`)

`internal` types may skip this line entirely. If an internal type sits at a place a reader might
reasonably expect public visibility (e.g. `StatValueValidation`), replace the summary with a
one-line reason it's internal instead (e.g. `// Internal validation helpers; not part of the
public Stats API surface.`).

## Line length

Wrap `///` XML doc lines and `//` inline comments at **120 characters**. Break at phrase
boundaries; continue on the next doc or comment line with the same prefix (`///` or `//`).
Prefer shorter lines when a remark is only one or two sentences — do not pad to 120.

## Voice — avoid AI-flavored docs

This section governs **wording**, not structure. Placement / Tier 1/2/3 still decide whether a
type `summary` / `remarks`, member `//`, or optional `<exception>` belongs; Voice only cuts fluff
once those are justified.

Prefer short, specific contracts over polished essays. Good docs sound like a teammate warning
about a footgun, not a generated API brochure.

Signs to cut or rewrite:

- **Defensive framing** — "Not redundant with…", "It is important to note…", "By design…" as padding
- **Restating the summary in remarks** — if the type summary already says "Shared", don't open
  remarks with "Construct once and share…"
- **Member laundry lists in type remarks** — if the sentence names a member, move it to `//`
- **Stacking every why in one remark** — type remarks stay type-scoped; leave implementation
  trivia to `architecture.mdc`
- **Step-list summaries** that only narrate the method body
- **Uniform templates** across sibling types
- **Marketing / jargon padding** — "diminishing-returns curve", "composition-root contract" when
  a plain sentence works

## Inline comments

Prefer **`//`** for member-local footguns. One line, why-not-what. See Placement. Multi-fact
architecture that is not tied to one member belongs in type `<remarks>`, `architecture.mdc`, or
local `ARCHITECTURE_Detailed.md` — not multi-line essays above a method.

```csharp
// Correct — one line, explains the non-obvious part
// DoT bypasses DamagePipeline by design — TakeDamage only, no DamageEvent attribution.
public void OnTick(BuffInstance instance, ICombatEntity target, float deltaTime)
{
    target.Damageable.TakeDamage(instance.Config.DamagePerSecond * deltaTime);
}
```

Wrong: multi-sentence “architecture essays” above a method, or comments that only narrate what
the code already says.
